4 A BILL FOR AN ACT ENTITLED: “AN ACT GENERALLY REVISING WORKERS' COMPENSATION LAWS
5 RELATING TO EVIDENTIARY STANDARDS; PROVIDING THAT THE CLAIMANT HAS A BURDEN OF
6 PROOF; PROVIDING EVIDENTIARY STANDARDS FOR OPINIONS OF TREATING PHYSICIANS;
7 ALLOWING FOR CERTAIN INDEPENDENT MEDICAL EXAMINATIONS BY THE INSURER; AND AMENDING
8 SECTION 39-71-605, MCA.”
9
10 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF MONTANA:
11
12 NEW SECTION. Section 1. Evidentiary standard. (1) The claimant has the burden of proof on a
13 more probable than not basis for all matters at issue.
14 (2) Opinions of the treating physician are not entitled to deference.
15 (3) Testimony of a health care professional must be weighed based on the individual's education,
16 training, experience, expertise in the medical field in question, and credibility.
17 (4) Rule 30(b)(6) of the Montana Rules of Civil Procedure relating to depositions and discovery
18 may not be permitted under this title.
19 (5) Discovery related to an independent medical examiner is limited to the provider's training,
20 educational background, the number of independent medical exams performed each year, the number of
21 independent medical exams for the particular insurer named as a respondent, and payments received from the
22 particular insurer named as the respondent.
23 (6) Discovery requests regarding the independent examiner's personal finances are prohibited.
24
25 Section 2. Section 39-71-605, MCA, is amended to read:
26 "39-71-605. Examination of employee by physician -- effect of refusal to submit to examination
27 -- report and testimony of physician -- cost. (1) (a) Whenever in case of injury the right to compensation
28 under this chapter would exist in favor of any employee, the employee shall, upon on the written request of the
